<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:34<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720b360682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:34.</label.designator><headtext>Ancient documents</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51dbd0307fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(16)</cite.query> provides for the general admission of statements in “ancient documents.” <eos/><bos/>This provision recognizes a document as ancient at 20 years.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Recitals in ancient documents are received as evidence of the facts stated.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a95a007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The new Code does not require a subscribing witness in most cases as long as the authenticity of the document is established.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a95a017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>An application for life insurance, authenticated as an ancient document, was received to prove the age of the applicant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a95a027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A letter attached to a warranty deed, purporting to be a part of the transaction, was admissible as an ancient document.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a95a037fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Possession consistent with the deed is an added requirement in regard to ancient deeds.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a95a047fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] Usually this means possession under the deed[<footnote.reference refid="Ic5a981107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] but is not entirely required if possession or lack of possession is consistent. <eos/><bos/>For example, in the case of wild lands, the fact that no one was in actual possession was consistent with the <page no="341"/>deed.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a981117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] In some cases, the Georgia Supreme Court indicated that there must have been possession <ital>inconsistent</ital> with the deed to prevent its admission as an ancient document and that a short period of adverse possession was not enough.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5a981127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic5a95a007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="0280312812" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="I51dc1e507fc011ea988285db8533e975">McCormick on Evidence § 323 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a95a017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-903" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51dc6c707fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-903</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a95a027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1935106856" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I51dce1a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">McDay v. Metropolitan Life Ins. Co., 51 Ga. App. 791, 181 S.E. 871 (1935)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a95a037fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1952104884" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I51dd56d27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Shaw v. Crawford, 208 Ga. 595, 68 S.E.2d 598 (1952)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="341"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a95a047fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST44-5-45" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51dda4f07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 44-5-45</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a981107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1905012040" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I51de1a227fc011ea988285db8533e975">Lanier v. Hebard, 123 Ga. 626, 51 S.E. 632 (1905)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1952104884" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I51de1a257fc011ea988285db8533e975">Shaw v. Crawford, 208 Ga. 595, 68 S.E.2d 598 (1952)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a981117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1888168794" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I51de8f527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Prigden v. Green, 80 Ga. 737, 7 S.E. 97 (1888)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5a981127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1873004840" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I51df04817fc011ea988285db8533e975">Doe ex dem. v. Roe, 49 Ga. 165, 1873 WL 2396 (1873)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017193" w-serial-number="1926105638" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I51df04857fc011ea988285db8533e975">Gaskins v. Guthrie, 162 Ga. 103, 132 S.E. 764 (1926)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:34<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.blo